 Humberside, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hull, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1597–":"about 1597–Deceased","1600–Female":"1600–Deceased","1617–1703":"1617–1703","1597–Male":"1597–Deceased","1600":"1600","1597":"1597","about 1597":"about 1597","1617":"1617","1703":"1703","Hull, Humberside, England, United Kingdom":"Hull, Humberside, England, United Kingdom","Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hull, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chapman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a merchant or trader, Middle English <i>chap(pe)man</i>, <i>chepman</i>, Old English <i>cēapmann</i>, <i>cēpemann</i>, a compound of <i>cēap</i> ‘barter, bargain, price, property’ + <i>mann</i> ‘man’.","Jewish: adopted probably for a like-sounding or like-meaning name in some other European language; see for example   Kaufman  .","History: This name was brought independently to North America from England by numerous different bearers from the 17th century onward. John Chapmen (sic) was one of the free planters who assented to the ‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatman","meanings":["English: altered form of   Chapman  ."]},{"name":"Kaufman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Chaim, Emanuel, Moshe, Eytan, Herschel, Zvi, Ari, Aron.","Americanized form of German   Kaufmann  , and a variant of the same Jewish surname.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the personal name <i>Kaufman</i> meaning ‘merchant’. Compare   Koyfman   2."]},{"name":"Chipman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>chipman</i> (Old English <i>cȳp(e)mann</i>), a side form of <i>chapman</i>, <i>chepman</i> ‘merchant, trader’; see   Chapman  , with which this name was interchangeable."]},{"name":"Copeman","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): patronymic from the early Middle English personal name <i>Cop(e)man</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Scandinavian <i>Kaupmaðr</i>. It is a transferred use of Old Scandinavian <i>kaupmaðr</i> (Old Danish <i>køpman</i>) ‘merchant’, cognate with Old English <i>cēapmann</i> (see   Chapman  ), but there is no evidence for the occupational term in Middle English.","Americanized form of North German   Koopmann   or Dutch   Koopman  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert John Chapman was born about 1597, in Hull, Humberside, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Robert John Chapman."},"et":{"about 1597–":"umbes 1597–Surnud","1600–Female":"1600–Surnud","1617–1703":"1617–1703","1597